# Avoid `clamp()` For Responsiveness

Do not use CSS `clamp()` as the default way to make typography, spacing, widths, heights, or offsets responsive. Some target devices and browsers may not handle dynamic clamp-based sizing consistently.

## Preferred Approach

- Use explicit breakpoint styles through CSS media queries, CSS Modules, or Tailwind responsive variants.
- Use stable `px` values or project tokens for spacing, sizing, radii, and layout measurements.
- Test important responsive changes at the actual target widths instead of relying on fluid formulas.
- Prefer separate desktop, tablet, and mobile declarations when a value needs to change across devices.

## Avoid

```css
.title {
  font-size: clamp(32px, 5vw, 72px);
}
```

## Prefer

```css
.title {
  font-size: 32px;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .title {
    font-size: 48px;
  }
}

@media (min-width: 1280px) {
  .title {
    font-size: 72px;
  }
}
```
